1
00:00:00,050 --> 00:00:05,564
You're listening to: Idempotency Keys: How We Stopped Double-Charging Customers.

2
00:00:05,564 --> 00:00:09,639
A retry on a slow payment request charged a customer twice.

3
00:00:09,639 --> 00:00:20,552
A practical guide to idempotency keys — how to design the key, store it atomically, handle in-flight duplicates, and make any unsafe POST safe to retry.

4
00:00:20,552 --> 00:00:21,598
Let's get started.

5
00:00:21,598 --> 00:00:26,358
The email I never want to receive: "I was charged twice for one order."

6
00:00:26,358 --> 00:00:33,281
We looked, and it was true — two identical payments, eight seconds apart, same amount, same customer.

7
00:00:33,281 --> 00:00:35,228
No bug in our charging logic.

8
00:00:35,228 --> 00:00:36,322
No double-click.

9
00:00:36,322 --> 00:00:39,254
The customer pressed "Pay" exactly once.

10
00:00:39,254 --> 00:00:45,576
The cause was a retry — and it is one of the most common, most expensive bugs in distributed systems.

11
00:00:45,576 --> 00:00:48,245
The fix is idempotency keys.

12
00:00:48,245 --> 00:00:56,213
This post is the practical version: how the double-charge happens, and how to make any unsafe operation safe to repeat.

13
00:00:56,213 --> 00:01:03,353
It builds on ideas in REST API design best practices and rate limiting & API gateway patterns.

14
00:01:03,353 --> 00:01:07,031
Now, let's talk about How one click becomes two charges.

15
00:01:07,031 --> 00:01:09,495
Here is the timeline of our incident:

16
00:01:09,495 --> 00:01:14,026
The client POSTs /payments to charge ₹2,000..

17
00:01:14,026 --> 00:01:18,149
Our server receives it, calls the payment gateway, the charge succeeds..

18
00:01:18,149 --> 00:01:23,978
While we are writing the success response, the request takes longer than the client's 10-second timeout..

19
00:01:23,978 --> 00:01:30,877
The client gives up, sees a timeout, and — being a well-behaved client — retries the same request..

20
00:01:30,877 --> 00:01:39,170
Our server receives the retry as a brand-new request, calls the gateway again, charges ₹2,000 a second time..

21
00:01:39,170 --> 00:01:40,949
Nobody did anything wrong.

22
00:01:40,949 --> 00:01:42,680
The network was slow once.

23
00:01:42,680 --> 00:01:48,076
The deadly combination is a non-idempotent operation + an automatic retry.

24
00:01:48,076 --> 00:01:56,370
And retries are everywhere: client libraries retry, load balancers retry, mobile apps retry on flaky connections.

25
00:01:56,370 --> 00:02:02,271
If your "create payment" endpoint isn't safe to call twice, it is only a matter of time.

26
00:02:02,271 --> 00:02:04,555
Moving on to What "idempotent" means.

27
00:02:04,555 --> 00:02:11,442
An operation is idempotent if performing it multiple times has the same effect as performing it once.

28
00:02:11,442 --> 00:02:16,634
GET, PUT, and DELETE are idempotent by definition in HTTP.

29
00:02:16,634 --> 00:02:22,656
POST is not — and "charge a card" is the canonical non-idempotent operation.

30
00:02:22,656 --> 00:02:25,997
You cannot change the semantics of "charge a card."

31
00:02:25,997 --> 00:02:31,935
But you can attach a token that lets the server recognize a retry and refuse to do the work twice.

32
00:02:31,935 --> 00:02:34,759
That token is the idempotency key.

33
00:02:34,759 --> 00:02:38,401
Next up: The design: a client-generated key.

34
00:02:38,401 --> 00:02:45,757
The client generates a unique key (a UUID) for each logical operation and sends it with the request.

35
00:02:45,757 --> 00:02:49,182
Crucially, a retry reuses the same key.

36
00:02:49,182 --> 00:02:56,478
The server stores the key and the result; if it sees the key again, it returns the stored result instead of re-executing.

37
00:02:56,478 --> 00:03:01,730
This is exactly how Stripe, PayPal, and every serious payments API work.

38
00:03:01,730 --> 00:03:08,906
The key belongs to the operation, not the attempt — so the first try and every retry carry the same key.

39
00:03:08,906 --> 00:03:12,896
Let's explore The naive implementation (and its race condition).

40
00:03:12,896 --> 00:03:14,242
The obvious version:

41
00:03:14,242 --> 00:03:16,802
This is better, but it has a race.

42
00:03:16,802 --> 00:03:24,567
Two requests with the same key can both pass the find(key) check before either inserts — and you are back to double-charging.

43
00:03:24,567 --> 00:03:26,983
The "check, then act" gap is the bug.

44
00:03:26,983 --> 00:03:28,906
You must make claiming the key atomic.

45
00:03:28,906 --> 00:03:31,021
Now let's look at The correct implementation.

46
00:03:31,021 --> 00:03:34,555
Use a unique constraint and let the database arbitrate.

47
00:03:34,555 --> 00:03:39,146
Insert the key first, in a PENDING state, before doing any work.

48
00:03:39,146 --> 00:03:42,872
The unique constraint guarantees exactly one winner.

49
00:03:42,872 --> 00:03:45,192
Three cases are now handled correctly:

50
00:03:45,192 --> 00:03:50,048
First request: claims the key, charges once, stores the result..

51
00:03:50,048 --> 00:03:55,913
Retry after completion: unique-violation → finds completed → replays the stored response.

52
00:03:55,913 --> 00:03:57,391
No second charge..

53
00:03:57,391 --> 00:04:08,701
Concurrent duplicate (original still running): unique-violation → finds pending → returns 409, so the client backs off and retries, eventually getting the replayed result..

54
00:04:08,701 --> 00:04:16,081
That in-flight case is the one the naive version misses, and it is exactly the 8-seconds-apart scenario that bit us.

55
00:04:16,081 --> 00:04:19,278
Now, let's talk about Details that matter in production.

56
00:04:19,298 --> 00:04:21,255
Scope the key to the request.

57
00:04:21,255 --> 00:04:24,752
Store a hash of the request body alongside the key.

58
00:04:24,752 --> 00:04:33,695
If the same key arrives with a different body, that is a client bug — reject it (422) rather than silently replaying an unrelated result.

59
00:04:33,695 --> 00:04:35,293
Set a TTL.

60
00:04:35,293 --> 00:04:38,586
Idempotency keys don't need to live forever.

61
00:04:38,586 --> 00:04:44,452
We expire them after 24 hours, which comfortably covers any realistic retry window.

62
00:04:44,452 --> 00:04:49,993
A periodic job (or a Redis TTL, if you store keys there) handles cleanup.

63
00:04:49,993 --> 00:04:51,531
Pick the right storage.

64
00:04:51,531 --> 00:05:02,781
Redis with SET key value NX EX 86400 is a great fit for the atomic claim and the TTL — the same NX single-flight trick I used to stop a cache stampede.

65
00:05:02,781 --> 00:05:08,911
A relational table with a unique constraint is just as correct and gives you durability for free.

66
00:05:08,911 --> 00:05:12,829
Either works; the non-negotiable property is atomic claim.

67
00:05:12,829 --> 00:05:15,365
Return the key boundary clearly.

68
00:05:15,365 --> 00:05:20,534
Document that clients must generate one key per operation and reuse it on retry.

69
00:05:20,534 --> 00:05:25,606
An idempotency system only works if clients hold up their half of the contract.

70
00:05:25,606 --> 00:05:28,034
Moving on to Where else to apply this.

71
00:05:28,034 --> 00:05:37,793
Once you have the pattern, you start seeing non-idempotent endpoints everywhere: "send invitation email," "create order," "submit insurance claim," "publish event."

72
00:05:37,793 --> 00:05:43,623
Any POST that has a side effect and might be retried should accept an idempotency key.

73
00:05:43,623 --> 00:05:49,993
It is cheap insurance against the most embarrassing class of bug — doing something irreversible twice.

74
00:05:49,993 --> 00:05:51,880
Next up: The takeaway.

75
00:05:51,880 --> 00:05:58,286
Retries are not a failure of your clients; they are a feature of resilient systems, and they are not going away.

76
00:05:58,286 --> 00:06:01,423
The server's job is to make repetition harmless.

77
00:06:01,423 --> 00:06:13,118
An idempotency key + an atomic claim + a stored result turns "charge the card" — the scariest operation in the system — into something you can safely call as many times as the network demands.

78
00:06:13,118 --> 00:06:21,123
We shipped this, replayed the failure in staging (slow response + client retry), and watched it charge exactly once.

79
00:06:21,123 --> 00:06:23,346
The double-charge emails stopped.

80
